despread and long-term circulation of plague tracts, which described the causes and signs of the disease, offered advice for preventing infection, and recommended therapies in a largely consistent style. What, where, and especially who was blamed for plague outbreaks changed considerably, however, as political, religious, economic, intellectual, medical, and even publication circumstances evolved.Patterns of Plague sheds light on what was consistent about plague thinking and what was idiosyncratic to particular places and times, revealing the many factors that influence how people understand and respond to epidemic disease.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMedical literaturezEnglandxHistory and criticism. 0aMedical literaturezFrancexHistory and criticism. 0aPlague in literature. 0aPlaguezEnglandxEpidemiologyxHistory. 0aPlaguezEnglandxHistory. 0aPlaguezFrancexEpidemiologyxHistory. 0aPlaguezFrancexHistory. 7aHISTORY / Europe / General.2bisacsh  aBills.  aBlack Death.  aChristian.  aCounter Reformation.  aEnglish.  aEuropean.  aFifteenth.  aFrench.  aIslamic.  aJewish.  aLondon.  aLyon.  aMarseille.  aMortality.  aOttoman Empire.  aParis.  aTurks.  aapothecary.  abook production.  aclergy.  acopyists.  adiachronic.  aearly modern.  aeighteenth century.  aepidemic.  afourteenth.  ageography.  ahistory.  ahumanism.  aliterature.  amanuscript production.  amedicine.  amedieval.  aorigin.  aothering.  aoutbreak.  apandemic.  aphysician.  apoverty.  aprinters.  ascribes.  aseventeenth.  asixteenth.  aspread.  asurgeon.  asynchronic.  atractates.  atranslators.  atreatises.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311127214608iTitle is part of eBook package: